# Oral History Interview Guide

This guide is for volunteers, researchers, students, and community members collecting oral histories related to Orang Laut, Orang Pulau, Pulau Brani, and Singapore’s island and maritime communities.

## Purpose

The purpose of an oral history interview is to preserve lived memory in the speaker’s own voice.

The goal is not only to collect facts, but to understand feelings, relationships, places, rituals, everyday life, migration, work, food, faith, sea knowledge, and community belonging.

## Before the interview

Before beginning, make sure the interviewee understands:

- Who is conducting the interview
- Why the interview is being recorded
- How the recording or transcript may be used
- Whether it may appear online
- Whether AI tools may be used for transcription or translation
- Whether they can request edits, limits, or withdrawal later

Ask for consent before recording.

## Suggested opening script

Thank you for agreeing to share your memories. This interview is part of a community heritage effort to document the histories, lives, and traditions of Orang Laut, Orang Pulau, and island communities connected to Pulau Brani and Singapore’s southern islands.

You may choose not to answer any question. You may also ask us to pause or stop the recording at any time. After the interview, you may request corrections or let us know if there are parts you do not want shared publicly.

